Hot Work Permit:  With regard to hot work that may occur on or near the propane process, the Reno Terminal has developed a written contractor evaluation program and a Hot Work Permit program to document the evaluation of the fire prevention and protection requirements. The Hot Work Permit system is implemented prior to allowing activities that could result the generation of sparks (e.g. cutting and grinding) or that involve the use of open flames.

Contractor Safety:  The Reno Terminal uses contractors during periods of increased maintenance or construction activities. The Kiva Energy Reno Terminal evaluates and qualifies contractors who will work on the systems and equipment. Reno Terminal has procedures in place to ensure that contractors 

- perform their work in a safe manner;
- have appropriate knowledge and skills;
- are aware of the hazards of their workplace;
- understand what they should do in the event of an emergency;
- understand and follow site specific safety rules; and 
- inform plan personnel of any hazards that they find while performing their work. 

Effective implementation of the contractor safety program is accomplished by providing contractors with an orientation session that covers (1) a process overview, (2) information about the safety and health hazards, (3) emergency response plan requirements and (4) safe work practices prior to beginning their work. 

Propane Regulatory Framework:  The Facility implements the provisions of the following guidelines and regulations for this regulated substance. 

- API 650 & 620 - Tank Construction;
- ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code, Section VIII;
- ASME B31.3 - Process Piping;
- Nevada Administrative Code (NAC) of Regulations, Chapter 459; 
- National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) 5
